BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:82V6CrX2uDr9lG8CFbNTv
SUMMARY:Indigenous Peoples Community Day
DTSTAMP:20260308T063049Z
DTSTART:20260308T163000Z
DESCRIPTION:We are proud to be cohosting this event with the Muckleshoot In
	dian Tribe! Join us as we welcome members of Indigenous communities to the
	 Aquarium for a day of cultural learning\, storytelling and knowledge shar
	ing. This event is open to all members of Indigenous communities and those
	 eager to celebrate and learn more about Indigenous cultures.  Explore our
	 habitats and learn about career paths from Aquarium staff. Enjoy cultural
	 demonstrations from local tribes\, plus tales from Indigenous storyteller
	s. Grab your tickets for this exciting day of learning and celebration at 
	the Aquarium. Remember\, one ticket grants you access to all three Aquariu
	m buildings\, plus the day’s activities. Grab yours: https://www.seattleaq
	uarium.org/events/indigenous-peoples-community-day\n\nhttps://seatoday.6am
	city.com/events/#/details/indigenous-peoples-community-day/18079696/2026-0
	3-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/indigenous-peoples-commun
	ity-day/18079696/2026-03-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Aquarium\, 1483 Alaskan Way\, Pier 59\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:QPDDDVFW6QdKpgF-s-AQ3
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260308T063049Z
DTSTART:20260308T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-08T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:c6XOqIOc0aFO0J0qtSiX_
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260308T063049Z
DTSTART:20260308T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	3-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-03-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Dn-SKN72OFBdWcTf5suXJ
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260308T063049Z
DTSTART:20260308T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nhttps://seatoday.
	6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geometry-of-light/16795597
	/2026-03-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-03-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
